Local Duality Theorem


Suppose that the problem minimizef(𝐱)subject to𝐡(𝐱)=𝟎
\begin{align}
\operatorname{minimize} & f(\bm{x}) \\
\text{subject to} & \bm{h}(\bm{x}) = \bm{0}
\end{align}
 has a local solution at 𝐱*\bm{x}^\ast with corresponding value r*r^\ast and Lagrange multiplier 𝛌*\bm{\lambda}^\ast. Suppose also that 𝐱*\bm{x}^\ast is a regular point of the constraints and that the corresponding Hessian of the Lagrangian 𝐋*=𝐋(𝐱*)\bm{L}^\ast = \bm{L}(\bm{x}^\ast) is positive definite. Then the dual problem maximizeϕ(𝛌) 
\begin{align}
\operatorname{maximize} & \phi(\bm{\lambda})
\end{align}
 has a local solution at 𝛌*\bm{\lambda}^\ast with corresponding value r*r^\ast and 𝐱*\bm{x}^\ast as the point corresponding to 𝛌*\bm{\lambda}^\ast in the definition of ϕ\phi.






Proof


It is clear that 𝐱*\bm{x}^\ast corresponds to 𝛌*\bm{\lambda}^\ast in the definition of ϕ\phi. Now at 𝛌*\bm{\lambda}^\ast we have by Lemma 1, ∇ϕ(𝛌*)=−𝐡(𝐱*)⊤=𝟎,
\nabla \phi(\bm{\lambda}^\ast) = -\bm{h}(\bm{x}^\ast)^\top = \bm{0}, 
 and by Lemma 2, the Hessian of ϕ\phi is negative definite. Thus 𝛌*\bm{\lambda}^\ast satisfies the SOSC for an unconstrained maximum point of ϕ\phi. The corresponding value ϕ(𝛌*)\phi(\bm{\lambda}^\ast) is found from the definition of ϕ\phi to be r*r^\ast.
